Midgaard reads Akh'enet as a cautionary case against allowing legal process and ritual to share vocabulary. Akh'enet's administrative failure — water quotas acquiring funerary annotations, death ledgers acquiring ration penalties — parallels the Violet Compact's later corruption, where registry apparatus classified condemned persons as "arcane material." Both systems were designed for categorical separation; both were exploited precisely through that shared vocabulary. The Reckoning faction notes the parallel explicitly: Akh'enet's Nadir Palace (reconciling court authority, hydraulic regulation, and funerary cosmology in one ceremonial machine) is the architectural version of what the Sealed Names Apparatus attempted administratively. Midgaard's corridor position structurally resembles Akh'enet's crossroads function; the Violet Compact was intended to prevent the same institutional contamination. That it failed by the same mechanism is the lesson Reckoning draws. Continuity notes that Akh'enet's Reed Ledger Warden tradition — civilian institutional continuity through catastrophe — validates maintaining functional governance even through collapse. Reed Ledger Warden records are accepted as having partial validity; post-Collapse Akh'enet documents require enhanced provenance review.

