Kiess reads Akh'enet as the canonical example of institutional legitimacy without external accountability producing erosion regardless of whether the legitimating vocabulary is administrative or theological. The Moon Sovereign's Doctrine of the Ninth Descent used sensory deprivation and chant cadence to produce verdicts with unmatched social legitimacy; the Court eventually performed sentence-bindings on living petitioners accused of water-debt concealment. The line between correction and curse eroded by institutional design, not bad actors. Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine traces the parallel erosion: the Violet Compact's registry system eroded until condemned persons were classified as "arcane material" — sentence-binding under administrative rather than theological vocabulary, same effect. Akh'enet's lesson is that the anti-sealed-warrant clause is a structural constraint on Kiess's own governance, not merely a critique of predecessors — an internal mechanism preventing Kiess from sliding toward the Akh'enet pattern from within. No external accountability, no sustainable governance, regardless of vocabulary.

