Akh'enet failed because two legal traditions resisted permanent synthesis — oasis water law and pyramid funerary authority kept bleeding into each other until the institution collapsed under internal contradiction. Rakuen's founding ideal faced structurally related failure: founding administrative categories (temporary emergency welfare infrastructure, civic renewal obligations) were reinterpreted under disaster pressure until ration towers became permanent and labor drafts were renamed. Akh'enet's Nadir Palace — built to reconcile incompatible systems, failing because every faction defines "repair" differently — has a Rakuen parallel in the Promise Stones: carved founding compact pledges that every faction cites as evidence of their incompatible project. Both ruins preserve objects that multiple factions claim as authentic foundation. Akh'enet's Caravan Freeholds — distrusting all grand institutions but preserving practical memory better than any faction — resemble Rakuen's practical-memory keepers: people who know where water still rises and who can be paid.

