Akh'enet and the Saltglass Reach share structural DNA: both transformed geographic features into jurisdictional boundaries, both attempted to reconcile incompatible legal traditions through procedural compromise, both institutionalized documentation-as-legal-weight for passage. Akh'enet's "double rulings" (adjudicating cases under both surface and tomb law simultaneously) prefigure Mafdet's dual-attestation protocol. Some Mafdet scholars argue the Shoreward Conversion's success was informed by Akh'enet's failure: the coast simplified what the inland hinge overcomplicated. Dual attestation at Mafdet keeps two frameworks distinct rather than allowing bleed-through as Akh'enet's did. Akh'enet relic fragments reaching Mafdet are classified under a Quarantine Ledger sub-category because they carry both oasis and pyramid provenance signatures simultaneously — uniquely difficult under either standard framework. Hazard Scribes apply a protocol acknowledging both provenance signatures without requiring adjudication of which governs — a procedural solution to the incompatibility that Akh'enet tried to resolve institutionally and failed.

