Akh'enet's institutional failure demonstrates what happens when claim, evidence, and verdict are blurred. The Jackal Balance Court began as a legitimate adjudication body; its failure was progressive conflation of administrative authority with spiritual authority until it performed sentence-bindings on living petitioners. In Ushabti terms: the Court's claim (verdicts have cosmic weight) was never subjected to evidentiary standards; the evidence was provided by the Court itself; the verdict was issued by the same institution making the original claim. Circular self-authorization produced no external check. The Reed Ledger Wardens represent the corrective: their doctrine explicitly prevents institutional authority from self-expanding into adjacent domains. Scribe-Marshal Iset Ren's argument — that no ritual verdict could override emergency water distribution — is the Ushabti position in desert terms: civic survival claims are not subordinate to institutional authority claims; an institution claiming primacy must produce evidence that does not consist solely of its own prior assertions.

