Akh'enet's hydraulic infrastructure is the material substrate beneath its institutional history. The city was built on fractured limestone and basalt intrusions connected indirectly to the Deepwell Confluence aquifer network. Keeper-era calibration works — road gradients, drainage cuts, shadow-line anchor points built to absurd precision — still funnel movement better than newer improvisations. The Bellwind Collapse was hydraulic failure before institutional failure: tremor chains and pressure faults ruptured deep regulator shafts, causing aquifer backflow with saline surge into civic cisterns. Resonance bells and mass ledger flooding were consequences of hydraulic failure — engineering failure that the Jackal Balance Court interpreted as spiritual judgment. This misclassification is the central problem: saline aquifer backflow under fracture stress is a predictable consequence of undersluice infrastructure on limestone over a pressured aquifer without fault-monitoring. The Sepulchrists' interpretation (divine judgment) and the Wardens' interpretation (engineering failure) are not equally valid readings. Current broken pressure logic, irregular echoes, and bioluminescent mineral films are consequences of unmanaged infrastructure, not active judgment.

